#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:87
msgid "Why pay for the same electricity twice?"
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:89
msgid ""
"\n"
"    On sunny hours, currently installed renewable sources sometimes produces more solar power "
"than the grid can absorb locally.\n"
"    That energy may go unused while other, less clean sources stay in the mix—so "
"consumers can end up paying for\n"
"    flexibility and constraints twice over.\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:96
msgid ""
"\n"
"    <strong>What helps?</strong> Stronger grids and storage (batteries) over time—and"
" market signals that reward\n"
"    using clean power when it is abundant, which can reduce waste and "
"ease bills.\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:104
msgid "City-sized picture"
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:106
#, python-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"    Today’s wasted solar total is in the ballpark of the daily "
"electricity of about\n"
"    <strong>%(homes)s</strong> typical homes, using an illustrative "
"%(kwh)s kWh per home per day\n"
"    for the analogy (not a census count—see methodology).\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:115
msgid "Methodology"
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:117
msgid ""
"\n"
"    Quarter-hourly unused solar energy (MWh) is derived from Red "
"Eléctrica de España (REE) data.\n"
"    It is processed in a separate pipeline and stored in this project’s "
"database before it is shown here:\n"
"    each row is keyed by date in 15-minute buckets.\n"
"    Multiple rows for the same day are summed bucket-wise before display."
"\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:125
msgid ""
"\n"
"    The chart aggregates those quarter-hours into 24 hourly bars "
"(Europe/Madrid calendar day). Any slots\n"
"    beyond the first 96 are folded into the last hour of the day. Day "
"totals are the sum of all\n"
"    quarter-hour values. “So far this year” uses SUM(total_mwh) across "
"rows from 1 January through the\n"
"    selected date. The average “per hour” figure is the mean of the 24 "
"hourly bars (equivalently the\n"
"    day total divided by 24).\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:134
msgid ""
"\n"
"    Euro amounts are set at"
" simple illustrative rates\n"
"    times energy, not a market settlement.\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:139
msgid "Household analogy"
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:141
msgid ""
"\n"
"    The household comparison uses a configurable illustrative kWh/day "
"figure to give an intuitive\n"
"    scale; replace or calibrate it when you publish official assumptions."
"\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#: wasted_sun/templates/day.html:149
